# Summary of Article

## Source and Content Type
This is historical data from the U.S. Energy Information Administration (EIA) showing daily spot prices for U.S. Gulf Coast Kerosene-Type Jet Fuel in dollars per gallon.

## Key Facts and Statistics

**Data Coverage:**
- The table presents daily (Monday-Friday) jet fuel spot prices
- Time period shown: April 1990 through mid-April 1994 (data appears to be cut off)
- Prices are reported as "Spot Price FOB" (Free On Board)

**Price Range Observations from the Historical Data:**
- **1990:** Prices started around $0.50-0.55/gallon in April, spiked dramatically to $1.43/gallon in October (likely related to Gulf War), then declined to around $0.80-0.90/gallon by year-end
- **1991:** Prices began around $0.80/gallon in January, dropped sharply to $0.55-0.60/gallon by March-April, and remained relatively stable in the $0.55-0.70/gallon range through year-end
- **1992:** Prices ranged mostly between $0.50-0.65/gallon throughout the year
- **1993:** Prices generally stayed in the $0.45-0.58/gallon range, with a notable dip to the low $0.40s in December
- **1994 (partial):** Prices started around $0.45-0.50/gallon in early January, briefly spiked to nearly $0.60/gallon mid-January, then declined back to the $0.43-0.47/gallon range by late March/early April

## Note
This article contains only historical price data and does not include any analysis, forecasts, or expert opinions regarding future jet fuel prices. The data ends in 1994 and does not provide information relevant to forecasting March 2026 prices.
